attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This MIPS binary is a botnet agent, specifically a variant of the Mirai/Gafgyt families commonly targeting IoT devices. The sample exhibits several definitive malicious behaviors: it contains an extensive embedded credential table (sub_4100f8) with hundreds of common default username/password pairs (e.g., 'root', 'admin', 'vizxv', 'supportadmin') used for automated brute-force propagation. It features a downloader component (sub_40fcf0) that issues HTTP GET requests for '/dlr.' and leverages 'busybox' utilities like wget, tftp, and ftpget to fetch additional payloads. Furthermore, it scans the /proc filesystem to identify and terminate competing processes (sub_400670, sub_40b478) and uses direct syscalls for networking (socket, connect, send, recv) to evade detection. Relevant IOCs include command templates for payload execution ('.d', '.ffaaxx') and strings associated with automated telnet/SSH exploitation.
